In [17]:
def plot_corr(df, size=11):
    corr = df.corr()
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(size, size))
    ax.matshow(corr)
    plt.xticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns)
    plt.yticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns)
    for (i, j), z in np.ndenumerate(corr):
        ax.text(j, i, '{:0.1f}'.format(z), ha='center', va='center')

Business Understanding¶

Confusion matrix means True Positive (observed=1,predicted=1):

Predicted that the customer will accept a personal loan in the next campaign.

False Positive (observed=0,predicted=1):

Predicted that the customer would accept the personal loan during the campaign but did not.

True Negative (observed=0,predicted=0):

Predicted that customer would not accept the personal loan during the campaign and did not accept.

False Negative (observed=1,predicted=0):

redicted that customer would not accept the personal load during the campaign and did accept it.

Important Features

'Education' 'Family' 'CCAvg' 'CD Account' 'Experience' 'Income'

seems to be top 6 features which influence the model's output. Based on the coefficients value.

Important Metric

Here Thera Bank wants to focus on targeting liability customers represented as true positive values from the confusion matrix. The majority of the true positive personnel were educated with a family. Suppose Thera Bank targets the campaign at a different group of people. In that case, they are likely to encounter false-positive personal and waste money on advertising to them, as they are unlikely to take a personal loan out from the bank due to the campaign.
